Helment.js::  Rate Limiting :: CSRF protection


Helmet.js:
-------------------- >
# Helmet.js is an Express middleware that sets various HTTP response headers to protect your application from well-known web vulnerabilities. 
# Helmet → browser-level protection

# Those headers are not just metadata — they directly control how browsers behave, and that affects your app’s security.
# Helmet.js adds security-related HTTP headers automatically so you don’t have to manually configure them.

Without Helmet What happens:
------------------------------------------- >

By using the helmet :
------------------------------- >
X-Frame-Options: DENY
>>> Completely blocks your site from being loaded in any iframe

#  Clickjacking attack

What this attack will do:

1. Attacker creates a malicious page
They design a page that looks normal (like a game, button, or reward).
2. They embed your app in an invisible iframe.
<iframe src="https://your-app.com/delete-account" style="opacity:0; position:absolute;"></iframe>
3.They place fake UI.
A button saying 👉 “Click here to win ₹1000”
But behind that button…
👉 The real button is from your app (like “Delete Account” or “Transfer Money”)


# XSS (Cross-Site Scripting policy ) :
  >>> CSP restricts which scripts can run and helps mitigate XSS, but it must be configured properly.
  >>>  It can completely block inline script injection even if an attacker finds an XSS hole.

What this attack will do:
Attackers inject scripts into your app.

# MIME sniffing attacks :
  >>> Normally , servers tell browsers what a file is using a header.
     ex: content-Type: text/html 
  >>> This is an HTML, render it as a webpage.

By usning helmet ::  X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff 
here, Tell browser "Do not Guess"

# X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff: 
  >>> Browser tries to guess file types → can execute malicious files.
  >>> Browsers sometimes ignore the header and try to guess (sniff) the file type.

# Information Leakage:
  >>> Your server might expose tech stack like: X-Powered-By: Express
  >>> Helmet removes it → attackers get less info.

# Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy (CORP)
  >>> Helmet adds this: Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy: same-origin
  >>>  It Prevents other sites from loading your resources.


# Cache-Control
  >>> Helmet adds This:  Cache-Control: no-store
  >>> Helmet does NOT automatically set Cache-Control: no-store
  >>> You must configure it manually

ex: Prevents sensitive data from being cached

# Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS)
  >>> With out this , any can be used like, http, https, etc
  >>> When we enable this, Strict-Transport-Security 
  Forces to use HTTPS

Implementation of the Helmet in Express:
-------------------------------------------------------- >
npm install helmet

const express = require('express');
const helmet = require('helmet');
const app = express();

// Simplest usage — enables ALL defaults at once
app.use(helmet());

Note: It should be combined with other security mechanisms like input validation, authentication, CSRF protection, and rate limiting to build a secure backend system.

